            <article id="text_paragraphs">
                <h2>Understanding CSS Specificity</h2>
                <p>
                    <mark>CSS specificity</mark> determines which style rules apply when multiple conflicting rules target the same element. It's calculated based on the combination of selectors used in the rule.
                </p>
                <h2>Exploring Complex Selectors</h2>
                <p>
                    <mark>Complex selectors</mark> in CSS involve combining multiple simple selectors to target elements more specifically. They include descendant selectors, child selectors, and more.
                </p>
                <h2>Differentiating Pseudo-classes and Pseudo-elements</h2>
                <p>
                    <mark>Pseudo-classes</mark> specify a special state of the selected element, like ":hover" for mouse-hover effect. <mark>Pseudo-elements</mark> target specific parts of an element, such as "::before" and "::after" for inserting content before and after an element.
                </p>
            </article>
            <article id="text__blockquotes">
